00:13:25,330 --> 00:13:26,752
future of jobs looked like.

271
00:13:26,752 --> 00:13:28,193
And we were talking about the singularity.

272
00:13:28,193 --> 00:13:29,835
And it was a lot of things we were talking about, like, hey,

273
00:13:29,835 --> 00:13:30,495
what if jobs went away?

274
00:13:30,495 --> 00:13:32,377
What would the world look like?

275
00:13:32,377 --> 00:13:34,459
And then we started rolling that into the actual game.

276
00:13:34,459 --> 00:13:37,062
And the premise is that it's the year 2050 and robots have

277
00:13:37,062 --> 00:13:38,523
taken all human jobs.

278
00:13:38,523 --> 00:13:39,764
And that the job simulator is actually a

279
00:13:40,045 --> 00:13:44,627
historical recreation of what it was like to job. It was no longer the simulator trying to teach

280
00:13:44,627 --> 00:13:48,849
you how to job correctly. It was the robots trying to figure out what it was like to job so

281
00:13:48,849 --> 00:13:54,232
that future humans could experience the same thing. But with poor Wikipedia skills that they

282
00:13:54,232 --> 00:13:56,393
kind of skimmed and said, I guess that's how it worked.

283
00:13:58,506 --> 00:14:03,348
And so having that strong premise meant that we could have a better process.

284
00:14:03,348 --> 00:14:06,910
Well, we had a better design process throughout and writing process throughout.

285
00:14:06,910 --> 00:14:11,232
So, for example, one of our first tasks in the kitchen was you have to make soup.

286
00:14:11,232 --> 00:14:16,235
And so with the simplicity of what we were trying to do with picking up objects and throwing them,

287
00:14:16,235 --> 00:14:20,257
we thought, okay, why don't we just make it so that you toss a bunch of items into a pot arbitrarily?

288
00:14:21,166 --> 00:14:23,968
and out comes a fully formed can of soup.

289
00:14:23,968 --> 00:14:25,850
Because I guess the robots didn't know

290
00:14:25,850 --> 00:14:27,911
how a real soup making process worked

291
00:14:27,911 --> 00:14:29,052
and they saw the two pieces

292
00:14:29,052 --> 00:14:30,893
and put it together in their head.

293
00:14:30,893 --> 00:14:33,896
And so that allowed us to be really creative

294
00:14:33,896 --> 00:14:36,458
in how we were able to tackle design questions.

295
00:14:36,458 --> 00:14:38,739
Like we were able to use a microwave

296
00:14:38,739 --> 00:14:41,862
and kind of like label it as this elite cooking device

297
00:14:41,862 --> 00:14:42,782
that the top chefs would use.

298
00:14:42,782 --> 00:14:44,824
And so you could make a fully formed cake.

299
00:14:45,124 --> 00:14:49,071
by putting flour, bread, and something into,

300
00:14:49,071 --> 00:14:50,553
was it flour and?

301
00:14:50,553 --> 00:14:50,894
Eggs.

302
00:14:50,894 --> 00:14:51,154
Eggs.

303
00:14:51,154 --> 00:14:55,341
But it wasn't really flour, it was like a flour,

304
00:14:55,341 --> 00:14:55,742
with petals.

305
00:14:55,742 --> 00:14:59,488
So yeah, it's bad puns and combinations led to this.

306
00:14:59,867 --> 00:15:02,867
So we got to the point where we're starting to think,

307
00:15:02,867 --> 00:15:04,227
okay, we have something that's fun,

308
00:15:04,227 --> 00:15:06,648
now how do we do this, how do we do this?

309
00:15:06,648 --> 00:15:10,169
And it turned out, even the most simple things

310
00:15:10,169 --> 00:15:12,009
were extremely challenging in the early days.

311
00:15:12,009 --> 00:15:14,469
So the concept of how picking up items

312
00:15:14,469 --> 00:15:16,270
and the affordances should work visually,

313
00:15:16,270 --> 00:15:18,090
what does the hand show when you pick something up?

314
00:15:18,090 --> 00:15:20,251
What are the rules of all the physics interactions

315
00:15:20,251 --> 00:15:21,291
inside of VR?

316
00:15:21,291 --> 00:15:23,791
And so in these days, people were mostly

317
00:15:23,791 --> 00:15:25,272
just showing the controller visuals.

318
00:15:25,652 --> 00:15:28,693
and not many people had shown hand visuals.

319
00:15:28,693 --> 00:15:31,975
And the thing is, like grabbing inside of an item

320
00:15:31,975 --> 00:15:33,796
and it interpenetrates and showing your hand

321
00:15:33,796 --> 00:15:36,997
going through something, it just didn't feel great.

322
00:15:36,997 --> 00:15:40,839
And a lot of people were also building full arm IK

323
00:15:40,839 --> 00:15:43,320
on your first person view, so you'd look down

324
00:15:43,320 --> 00:15:45,662
and you'd see your elbow in a completely wrong spot

325
00:15:45,662 --> 00:15:47,723
because there's no way to really predict that data.

326
00:15:47,723 --> 00:15:49,564
So it was kind of a mess.

327
00:15:51,725 --> 00:15:54,226
thought that maybe we could just do a quick hack

328
00:15:54,226 --> 00:15:56,967
and try something where when you pick up an item,

329
00:15:56,967 --> 00:16:01,330
your hand just goes away to lessen the overlap effect.

330
00:16:01,330 --> 00:16:03,030
And it turned out, we had no idea,

331
00:16:03,030 --> 00:16:05,132
it turned out it was an extremely effective way

332
00:16:05,132 --> 00:16:08,253
and it had this kind of mental process

333
00:16:08,253 --> 00:16:11,235
that we dubbed tomato presence kind of as a joke,

334
00:16:11,235 --> 00:16:13,596
where you have hand presence with your hand.

335
00:16:14,036 --> 00:16:15,117
and then when you pick up an item

336
00:16:15,117 --> 00:16:16,997
and you remove the hand visual,

337
00:16:16,997 --> 00:16:19,258
the tomato acts as like a visual stand-in

338
00:16:19,258 --> 00:16:20,219
for where your hand is,

339
00:16:20,219 --> 00:16:21,759
and it's perfect rotation and perfect position,

340
00:16:21,759 --> 00:16:23,060
so you still have presence,

341
00:16:23,060 --> 00:16:25,781
it's just your hand presence turns into tomato presence.

342
00:16:25,781 --> 00:16:27,382
And so since the tomato was the first thing

343
00:16:27,382 --> 00:16:28,662
you encounter in the job,

344
00:16:28,662 --> 00:16:29,883
that's why we named it that,

345
00:16:29,883 --> 00:16:32,784
and now we've seen a multitude of GDC talks

346
00:16:32,784 --> 00:16:34,405
over the past couple years that refer to

347
00:16:34,405 --> 00:16:37,406
the official hiding hand technique as tomato presence.

348
00:16:37,406 --> 00:16:38,707
So write it down everyone,

349
00:16:38,707 --> 00:16:40,288
it's going in the textbooks, tomato presence.

